reviews_data.review_text:
Haraz isn’t your typical coffee house. There’s something more refined here—modern, polished, and layered with a character that feels both new and timeless.

The look, the vibe, the people… it all just works. I had a Haraz Latte with a raspberry-lemon kronut, grabbed a seat by the window, and let the Yemen music fill the space. It gave the moment this quiet elegance, the kind that makes you slow down and actually savor what’s in front of you.

It’s the kind of spot that stays with you long after you’ve left. And I’ll definitely be back.

Haraz Coffee in Charlotte brings something genuinely special to the coffee scene. The quality here stands out immediately — from the rich, authentic flavors to the warm and welcoming atmosphere. You can feel the care and intention behind everything they serve.

One thing I really love about this location is how fresh and creative everything is. They have their own bakers on-site, and the pastries and food taste like they came straight out of the oven. Their drinks and pastries are constantly evolving, with new items introduced regularly to match our changing tastes and keep things exciting.

My personal go-to is the Adeni chai — smooth, perfectly spiced, and one of the best chai drinks I’ve ever had anywhere. Paired with their pastries, it’s always a standout experience.

This Haraz location nails authenticity, quality, and innovation. If you want a coffee shop that truly cares about what they serve and always brings something fresh to the table, this is the spot. Highly recommend.

This Haraz location was very nice when it opened, but since has gone really far down hill. Dirty floors and windows. Workers do not know how to make all of the drinks and they are not cheap. Gnats and fruit flies throughout the seating area. It's a shame because it could be a really nice, convenient place for coffee.

Such a beautiful spot! The food and drinks were amazing, and the staff was so welcoming. You have to try the bee bites—they’re incredible!

reviews_data.review_text:
Haraz isn’t your typical coffee house. There’s something more refined here—modern, polished, and layered with a character that feels both new and timeless.

The look, the vibe, the people… it all just works. I had a Haraz Latte with a raspberry-lemon kronut, grabbed a seat by the window, and let the Yemen music fill the space. It gave the moment this quiet elegance, the kind that makes you slow down and actually savor what’s in front of you.

It’s the kind of spot that stays with you long after you’ve left. And I’ll definitely be back.

Haraz Coffee in Charlotte brings something genuinely special to the coffee scene. The quality here stands out immediately — from the rich, authentic flavors to the warm and welcoming atmosphere. You can feel the care and intention behind everything they serve.

One thing I really love about this location is how fresh and creative everything is. They have their own bakers on-site, and the pastries and food taste like they came straight out of the oven. Their drinks and pastries are constantly evolving, with new items introduced regularly to match our changing tastes and keep things exciting.

My personal go-to is the Adeni chai — smooth, perfectly spiced, and one of the best chai drinks I’ve ever had anywhere. Paired with their pastries, it’s always a standout experience.

This Haraz location nails authenticity, quality, and innovation. If you want a coffee shop that truly cares about what they serve and always brings something fresh to the table, this is the spot. Highly recommend.

This morning, like many times before, I came to this café for breakfast. It was 7:30 on a Sunday, and the place was completely empty. I was with my small French Bulldog — a calm, quiet, well-trained dog who is a certified service dog. He doesn’t bark, doesn’t run around, doesn’t bother anyone, and knows all the commands. Honestly, he behaves better than many kids in public spaces.

I’ve been coming here with him many times before, and it was never an issue. In fact, I’ve often seen other customers with dogs — even large breeds, and not service animals — and it was totally fine.
But today, we were simply turned away. I was told we could only get coffee to go — we weren’t allowed to sit and enjoy it inside.

Honestly, it felt hurtful and disappointing. In 2025, you’d think we’d have a better understanding of rights, laws, and basic human decency — especially when it comes to animals. Service animals are protected by law, and they shouldn’t be discriminated against.

It’s sad that a place I used to love made it so clear today that I’m no longer welcome. And no — it’s not about the coffee.👎

My family and I have visited the Plaza Midwood location of Haraz Coffee several times and always had a great experience. We were excited to check out their new South End location and it did not disappoint!

Our go to is still the Mafowar cardamom and cream— bold, fragrant, and creamy with just the right touch of sweetness. We also devoured a variety of pastries, especially anything with pistachios (seriously, get them all). The brioche and the especially the one with strawberries was sold out by the time we got there around 3 pm. Our savory favorite was the pastry with a nod to the everything bagel – filled with cream cheese and feta and cheese, reminiscent of a warm, flaky borek. Absolutely delicious!

The South End space is beautiful, bright, and spacious—perfect for working, studying, or casual networking. There is a warm, welcoming vibe, and the staff likes to go above and beyond to make us feel at home.
I also asked about parking & great news: there’s free parking for guests. Just scan the QR code at the counter and enter their voucher code for validation.

If you’re a fan of Yemeni coffee or just looking to try something different, Haraz Coffee is a must. and yes, you can even buy their beans to brew at home, which we highly recommend.

Enjoy!

Josephine Local Guide
